Alfonso Cuaron's "Roma," a black-and-white drama based on the director's own childhood in Mexico, won the Golden Lion at the Venice Film Festival on Saturday. The film, which will be streamed on Netflix as well as released in theaters, follows the life of a middle-class family in Mexico City in the 1970s. Cuaron is known for directing the 2013 Oscar-winning Hollywood blockbuster "Gravity," starring Sandra Bullock and George Clooney. Olivia Colman won Best Actress The prize for Best Actress went to Britain's Olivia Colman for her performance as England's Queen Anne in "The Favourite." The film also won the runner-up Grand Jury Prize. Best Actor went to Willem Dafoe for his role in the Vincent Van Gogh biopic "At Eternity's Gate." Westerns honored The Special Jury Prize went to Jennifer Kent, the only woman director among the 21 directors competing for the Golden Lion. She won the award for the revenge thriller "The Nightingale," whose male lead, Baykali Ganambarr, also won an award for best up-and-coming actor/actress. Read more: Venice film festival slammed for 'toxic masculinity' France's Jacques Audiard won the Silver Lion for the best director for his comedy Western "The Sisters Brothers." The brothers Joel and Ethan Coen from the United States won the prize for best screenplay for their Western "The Ballad of Buster Scruggs." The Venice Film Festival, which was established in 1932, making it the world's oldest, began on August 29. Read more:

